    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>St Thomas</placeName>
                <date>6' Jany 1851</date>
            </p>
            <p>My Dr <addressee>Mr Leeser</addressee></p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">It has pleased the Almighty to<lb/> relieve my poor son
                    <persName>Jacob Benjamin</persName> from this world<lb/> of care &amp; trouble,
                he died in our midst on the <date>27</date><lb/> Ulta on <date>23d of Tebet</date>
                last, after a protracted &amp; painful<lb/> illness, his mind was brought to a
                perfect resignation<lb/> of his makers will. I will feel obliged if you would<lb/>
                insert the following in the Occident</p>
            <p>Died at <placeName>St Thomas V I.</placeName> in the <date>23d of Tebet</date>
                corresponding<lb/> with the <date>27 of December</date> last <persName>Mr J B
                    Wolff</persName> eldest son of <persName role="author">A<lb/> Wolff</persName>
                of said <placeName>Island</placeName></p>
            <table cols="2" rows="5">
                <row>
                    <cell>The Bible subscription is up to</cell>
                    <cell>40—to be bound</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Occident &amp; Advocate</cell>
                    <cell>4—</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Occident</cell>
                    <cell>1—</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advocate</cell>
                    <cell>1—</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Prayer Books</cell>
                    <cell>4 setts to be bound</cell>
                </row>
            </table>
            <p>I expect an augmentation as soon as it is closed<lb/> I will send you a copy of the
                names of the Subscribers<lb/> &amp; other information.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Previous to the death of my Son he informed<lb/> me that he was
                indebted to a <add>?</add>
                <persName>Hill</persName> a Shoemaker</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>five dollars for a <del>?</del> pr of Boots; his shop is in<lb/>
                <placeName>5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Street below Walnut</placeName>, he also owes a
                Bill to a<lb/>
                <persName>Dr Hollingswarth</persName> which I must ask you to get &amp; send<lb/>
                me, &amp; inquire if he owed any thing to the Synagogue<lb/> informing me on those
                points</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Enclosed the Bank of St Thomas Bill No 2896<lb/> in <persName>Bevan
                    &amp; Humphreys</persName> for Thirty dollars. Twenty five<lb/> of which are for
                the set of prayer Books so long due you,<lb/> &amp; five dollars for payment of
                    <persName>Hill</persName> the Shoemaker's Bill<lb/> against my poor
                    <persName>Jacob</persName>, the receipt for which please to<lb/> send me.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">My son <persName>Daniel</persName> in <placeName>San
                    Francisco</placeName> wrote me on<lb/> the <date>30</date>
                <add>?</add> last that himself with others of your friends<lb/> in that city would
                send you by the following Steamer<lb/> an address on the subject of the treatment
                received by you<lb/> from your late Congregation, he is very indignant at it,<lb/> I
                say, you have acted with the high sense of honor<lb/> to yourself &amp; Our Ministry
                in general &amp; reflects seriously<lb/> in the parties who have been the cause of your<lb/>
                <add>?</add>, continue your trust in the God of <placeName>Israel</placeName><lb/>
                he will shield &amp; protect you for the good <del>of</del> you have<lb/>
                accomplished for the Sons of <persName>Jacob</persName>.</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p rend="indent(1)">In the affliction which it has pleased our maker<lb/> to give to me
                &amp; family I have three great consolations,<lb/> firstly that he was spared to die
                in the midst of those he<lb/> loved &amp; loved him, so that every earthly care
                &amp; attention was<lb/> extended <del>to him</del>, secondly his mind by frequent
                religious<lb/> admonitions was brought to a perfect state of resignation<lb/> to his
                makers will, this was a heavy &amp; heart breaking<lb/> task for me who had to do
                the duties appertaining to<lb/> a minister of which we are deprived by the
                opposition<lb/> of those adverse to doing their duty—thirdly the attendance<lb/> at
                his funeral was greater than ever witnessed in<lb/> this place &amp; at the Abel of
                Morning &amp; Evening we had<lb/> from 15 to 50 males of our people—the
                followers<lb/> at the funeral were Jews &amp; Christians, Colored, as<lb/> well as
                whites.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Those of our immediate friends that you know<lb/> I will be thankful
                that you communicate the mournful<lb/> intelligence</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Believe me my Dr <addressee>Mr Leeser</addressee></p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">Yours faithfully</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">
                <persName role="author">A. Wolff</persName>
            </p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>please forward the “Challenge Accepted” by first</p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Revd Mr I Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">
                <placeName>Philada.</placeName>
            </p>
            <p>via <placeName>New York</placeName></p>
